[size=18pt][color=#6B46C1][b]When nginx and Caddy Both Failed[/b][/color][/size]
[hr]

400+ miners. 9,600 requests per second. 15,000+ concurrent TLS connections. That's the load our network generates 24/7.

We tried nginx. We tried Caddy. [b]Both collapsed.[/b]

[b]nginx[/b] — the industry standard, the thing that runs half the internet — hit 4,200% CPU usage across 48 worker processes and started returning [b]87% 503 errors[/b] on mining submits. Miners couldn't submit their hashes. The network's billion-hash-per-second wall of security was being throttled by a reverse proxy.

[b]Caddy[/b] — the modern Go-based alternative — spawned 88,000 goroutines, ate [b]11.5 GB of RAM[/b], burned 3,785% CPU, and returned [b]78% 503 errors[/b]. Same result: miners locked out, hashrate dropping.

The root cause? Both proxies create a new TCP connection to the backend for every single request. At 9,600 requests per second, that's 9,600 TCP handshakes per second. The OS ran out of file descriptors. The backend got buried under connection storms. Mining stopped.

So we did what any reasonable blockchain project does: [b]we wrote our own.[/b]

[code]
+=====================================================================+
|                    THE PROXY MASSACRE                                |
+=====================================================================+
|                                                                     |
|  Metric            | nginx     | Caddy      | q-flux               |
|  ==================|===========|============|======================|
|  CPU Usage         | 4,200%    | 3,785%     | <100%                |
|  Memory            | ~2 GB     | 11.5 GB    | ~50 MB               |
|  Error Rate        | 87%       | 78%        | 0%                   |
|  Backend Conns     | 55,000    | 46,000     | 1,100                |
|  Goroutines/Workers| 48 procs  | 88,000     | 48 threads (pinned)  |
|  Mining Success    | 13%       | 22%        | 100%                 |
|                                                                     |
|  Same hardware. Same backend. Same 9,600 req/s load.               |
|  Server: Epsilon — 48 cores, 64 GB RAM, 10 Gbit NVMe              |
|                                                                     |
+=====================================================================+
[/code]

That's not a typo. [b]87% error rate[/b] down to [b]0%[/b]. [b]11.5 GB memory[/b] down to [b]50 megabytes[/b]. [b]4,200% CPU[/b] down to under [b]100%[/b].


[size=18pt][color=#6B46C1][b]What Is q-flux?[/b][/color][/size]
[hr]

q-flux is a [b]worker-per-core TLS reverse proxy[/b] built from scratch in Rust, purpose-built for high-throughput blockchain infrastructure. Memory safety without garbage collection, fearless concurrency, and zero-cost abstractions — Rust gives us the performance of C with the safety of a managed language.

[b]10,655 lines of Rust.[/b] 18 source files. 242 automated tests including fuzz testing and Criterion benchmarks. 6 benchmark suites. Zero third-party proxy frameworks — every line written by us.

[b]Source Code:[/b] [url=https://code.quillon.xyz]code.quillon.xyz[/url] (self-hosted git — browse the full q-flux crate and all 85+ crates)

The design is simple but radical: [b]one dedicated worker thread per physical CPU core[/b]. Each worker owns its own:

[list]
[li]TCP listener (kernel distributes connections via SO_REUSEPORT — no thundering herd)[/li]
[li]TLS acceptor (rustls with session resumption — no OpenSSL)[/li]
[li]HTTP parser (zero-allocation header parsing)[/li]
[li]Upstream connection pool (persistent keepalive — NOT one-connection-per-request)[/li]
[li]Metrics counters (no cross-thread locks in the hot path)[/li]
[/list]

No thread contention. No shared mutable state in the fast path. No garbage collector. No runtime. Just 48 independent workers, each pinned to a physical CPU core via [b]sched_setaffinity[/b], processing requests in complete isolation.

[code]
              +---------------------------------------------+
              |           q-flux (48 workers)                |
              |                                              |
  Miners ---->|  Worker 0 --> Core 0 --> Pool --> :8080       |
  (TLS 443)   |  Worker 1 --> Core 1 --> Pool --> :8080       |
              |  Worker 2 --> Core 2 --> Pool --> :8080       |
  Browsers -->|  ...                                          |
  (HTTPS)     |  Worker 47 -> Core 47 -> Pool --> :8080       |
              |                                              |
  P2P ------->|  WebSocket detect --> raw TCP passthrough     |
  (WSS)       |                                              |
              +---------------------------------------------+
                       |
                       v
              +---------------------------------------------+
              |  q-api-server (backend on port 8080)         |
              |  - Mining challenge/submit                   |
              |  - Blockchain sync (Turbo Sync)              |
              |  - SSE streaming (balances, blocks)          |
              |  - REST API (wallet, DEX, governance)        |
              +---------------------------------------------+
[/code]


[size=18pt][color=#6B46C1][b]Why nginx Failed (Technical Deep Dive)[/b][/color][/size]
[hr]

The failure wasn't nginx's fault per se — it was a fundamental architectural mismatch. Here's what happened:

[b]1. Connection: close kills everything.[/b]
When nginx proxies to an upstream, the default behavior creates a new TCP connection for each request. At 9,600 req/s, that's 9,600 connect() + close() syscalls per second, each requiring a 3-way TCP handshake, plus TIME_WAIT socket accumulation. Within minutes, the system had 55,000 backend connections.

[b]2. Worker process model doesn't scale for TLS.[/b]
nginx spawns N worker processes (not threads). Each process does its own TLS handshake. With 400+ miners doing frequent reconnections (mining submit cycles), the TLS handshake storm consumed all 48 cores just doing key exchange.

[b]3. No upstream connection pooling.[/b]
The keepalive upstream feature in nginx is a bolt-on. You need explicit configuration, careful tuning, and it still has limitations. q-flux was designed from day one around persistent upstream connections — each worker maintains a warm pool of keepalive connections to the backend. Connection reuse is the default, not an option.

[b]What q-flux does differently:[/b]

[list]
[li][b]Per-worker upstream pools[/b] — 48 workers × 16 connections = 768 persistent backend connections (vs 55,000)[/li]
[li][b]TLS session resumption[/b] — returning miners skip the full handshake, cutting TLS overhead by 90%[/li]
[li][b]Backpressure via semaphore[/b] — if the backend is slow, excess requests get immediate 503 instead of piling up (prevents the connection avalanche)[/li]
[li][b]Health-aware routing[/b] — unhealthy backends get skipped, with automatic recovery when they come back[/li]
[/list]


