[size=18pt][color=#6B46C1][b]Why This Matters[/b][/color][/size]
[hr]

Most blockchain projects use off-the-shelf infrastructure. nginx, HAProxy, Cloudflare, AWS ALB. That works fine — until it doesn't.

When 400+ miners are submitting hashes around the clock, the infrastructure layer IS the network. If the proxy drops 87% of mining submissions, that's 87% of network security vanishing. Miners give up. Hashrate drops. Security weakens.

Building our own proxy wasn't about reinventing the wheel. It was about building a wheel that actually fits our vehicle.

[b]q-flux is purpose-built for blockchain infrastructure:[/b]

[list]
[li][b]WebSocket-native[/b] — detects Upgrade headers and does raw TCP passthrough, perfect for SSE mining streams and P2P gossipsub[/li]
[li][b]libp2p-aware[/b] — understands peer identities, tracks per-peer bandwidth, applies circuit breakers to slow/abusive peers[/li]
[li][b]Super-cluster failover[/b] — if local backends go down, traffic automatically routes to remote peer servers. Zero configuration, zero downtime.[/li]
[li][b]Hot TLS reload[/b] — swap certificates without restarting, critical for Let's Encrypt auto-renewal[/li]
[/list]

No blockchain project at our scale has built their own reverse proxy from scratch. This is infrastructure usually left to Google, Cloudflare, or the nginx team. We did it in [b]4 weeks[/b], and it outperforms all of them for our use case.

[b]How super-cluster failover works:[/b]
q-flux knows about all servers in the network (Alpha, Beta, Gamma, Delta, Epsilon). Each worker tries local backends first (round-robin, skipping unhealthy ones). If [i]every[/i] local backend is down, q-flux automatically routes to remote peer servers on other physical machines — no DNS changes, no manual intervention, no user impact. When the local backend recovers, traffic shifts back automatically via inline health detection on the first successful response. The whole failover happens in milliseconds, transparently.


